To avoid this sort of thing, I use:<p><pre><code>    #include <stdio.h>
    void eg(int i) {
        int *j; // "j is a pointer and (hence) *j is an int"
        j = &i; // "Put the address of i into *j? Yup"
        *j = *j + 1;
        printf("%d\n", *j);
    }
    int main() {
        eg(4);
    }

</code></pre>
Perhaps this is because I am just used to it, but I really see very little room for confusion here. The common usage avoids confusion, if you do not insist on assignment at the time of declaration.<p>To address your second confusion, just keep in mind that strings are char arrays and an array's name is actually a pointer. Again, I find this very straightforward.
